Most Valuable Statistic¶

For a team to determine who they should draft, or how much they should be paying each of their players, it's important for them to know what trends lead to success in the league. Because of this, our aim in this project is to determine what statistic leads to overall success in the league. For the purposes of this project, we are disregarding playoffs, and considering the winning team to be the one with the most wins in the regular season.

During the course of the NBA, it's clear that there have been many changes in how the game is played, which leads to a lot of discourse over who the greatest player of all time would be. Because of this, we're going to be mapping out each of the seasons from 1980 to 2020, along with how different statistics correlate to success within the league. This will help us determine the overall trends within the league

Step 1) Pulling the Data¶

The first step is going to be to pull the information from the website basketball-reference.com as a starting point we're going to be pulling from the "Team Stats" table, available for each of the seasons.¶

While browsing the basketball-reference.com page, we were able to find that website presents each of the pages in a way that makes it easy to scrape programmatically.

In [9]:
baseurl ="https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" 
yearurl= 1980
endurl = ".html"
leaguestats = []
while (yearurl < 2022):
    r = requests.get(baseurl + str(yearurl) + endurl)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'lxml')
    commentedout = []
    for comment in soup.find_all(text = lambda text:isinstance(text,Comment)):
        commentedout.append(comment)
    for element in commentedout:
        if str(element).startswith('\n\n<div class="table_container" id="div_team-stats-base">'):
            #print(commentedout.index(element))
            correctindex = commentedout.index(element)
    newsoup = BeautifulSoup(commentedout[correctindex], 'html.parser' )
    leaguestats.append(pd.read_html(str(newsoup).replace("*",'')))
    yearurl+=1

The leaguestats array will contain a dataframe for each season, accessible through leaguestats[{targetyear} - 1980]¶

The information available is as follows, and is a total for that season:

G => Games Played | MP => Minutes Played | FG => Field Goals (a basket scored on any shot or tap other than a free throw)

FGA => Field Goal Attempts | FG% => Field Goal Percentage | 3P => 3-Point Field Goals

3PA => 3-Point Field Goal Attempts | 3P% => 3-Point Field Goal Percentage | 2P => 2-Point Field Goals

2PA => 2-Point Field Goals Attempts | 2P% => 2-Point Field Goal Percentage | FT => Free Throws

FTA => Free Throw Attempts | FT% => Free Throw Percentage | ORB => Offensive Rebounds | DRB => Defensive Rebounds

TRB => Total Rebounds | AST => Assists | STL => Steals | BLK => Blocks | TOV => Turnovers | PF => Personal Fouls

PTS => Points

In [11]:
baseurl ="https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" 
yearurl= 1980
endurl = ".html"
miscstats = []
while (yearurl < 2022):
    r = requests.get(baseurl + str(yearurl) + endurl)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'lxml')
    commentedout = []
    for comment in soup.find_all(text = lambda text:isinstance(text,Comment)):
        commentedout.append(comment)
        #print(comment)
    for element in commentedout:
        if str(element).startswith('\n\n<div class="table_container" id="div_misc_stats">'):
            #print(commentedout.index(element))
            correctindex = commentedout.index(element)
    newsoup = BeautifulSoup(commentedout[correctindex], 'html.parser' )
    miscstats.append(pd.read_html(str(newsoup).replace("*",'')))
    yearurl+=1

Step 2) Graph the averages over the seasons¶

In order to determine which statistic has a higher correlation with the success of a team in a particular season, the first step should be to determine the average of that statistic each year, and plot that average.

From there, we would be able to determine how the winning and losing teams in the league compare to the league average.

In [15]:
# miscstats and leaguestats contain the averages of all the data presented for each season
#Leaguestats
#3P => 3-Point Field Goals
#3PA => 3-Point Field Goal Attempts
#3P% => 3-Point Field Goal Percentage
# FGA => Field Goal Average
# FG% => Field Goal Percentage

YrHiRank = []
YrLoRank = []
fig1, ax = plt.subplots()
for i in range(len(miscstats)):
    # Because miscstats sorts by the team's rank in the season, we can pull the 
    # highest ranking team's information for each season by grabbing the head of that 
    # season's dataframe
    head = miscstats[i][0].head(1)['Team']
    YrHiRank.append(head[0])
    for i in miscstats[i][0]['Team']:
        # We use a similar approach to what was described above in order to pull
        # the lowest ranking team
        if i != 'League Average':
            tail = i
    YrLoRank.append(tail)
#print(YrLoRank)
years = []
HiStat = []
LoStat = []
for i in range(1980,2022):
    years.append(i)
ssn3pa = []
for i in range(len(leaguestats)):
    #We then plot the average, the highest ranking team, and the lowest ranking team
    for j in leaguestats[i][0]['Team']:
        if j == YrHiRank[i]:
            stat = leaguestats[i][0][leaguestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]
            HiStat.append(float(stat['3PA']))
            
        if j == YrLoRank[i]:
            stat = leaguestats[i][0][leaguestats[i][0]['Team'] == j]   
            LoStat.append(float(stat['3PA']))
                    
    leagueAttmptStat = float(leaguestats[i][0]["3PA"].tail(1))
    ssn3pa.append(leagueAttmptStat)
    
fig1.set_size_inches(10, 10, forward=True)
ax.plot(years,HiStat,'o')
ax.plot(years,LoStat,'^')
ax.plot(years,ssn3pa)
plt.title('3-Point Field Goal Attempts Per Year')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('3PA')
ax.legend(['Winners','Losers','league averages'])

Modifying our Approach¶

As you can see, there are sharp dips in every statistic in both the 1998-1999 season, and 2011-2012 season. After seeing this, and looking closely at the data, we saw that there was a lockout during those seasons. For the 1998-99 season, that resulted in the season being shortened to 50 regular season games per team. For the 2011-12 season, it resulted in the season being shortened to 66 regular season games per team.

In order to avoid having outliers in our data, we decided to change our approach to examining the average stats per game for each team in each season so that the data will not be as affected by the lockout. However, it's important to note that although the data is then normalized by the per game approach, it does not change that the players themselves might have been affected by the lockout, for example because the scheduling of games in lockout seasons is more condensed, this may lead to more injuries especially if those players are out of shape at the beginning of the season. This would be reflected by a change in performance during that season, i.e. worse statistics.

In addition to the team with the most and least wins, we will show the teams who achieved the maximum for each statistical category.

baseurl ="https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" 
yearurl= 1980
endurl = ".html"
pergamestats = []
while (yearurl < 2022):
    r = requests.get(baseurl + str(yearurl) + endurl)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'lxml')
    commentedout = []
    for comment in soup.find_all(text = lambda text:isinstance(text,Comment)):
        commentedout.append(comment)
        #print(comment)
    for element in commentedout:
        if str(element).startswith('\n\n<div class="table_container" id="div_team-stats-per_game">'):
            #print(commentedout.index(element))
            correctindex = commentedout.index(element)
    newsoup = BeautifulSoup(commentedout[correctindex], 'html.parser' )
    pergamestats.append(pd.read_html(str(newsoup).replace("*",'')))

The graph above depicts the average league-wide assists per game in every season, from 1980 to the present. The league average starts off extremely high at approximately 26 APG, but as the 90s and 00s come around, they decrease to about 20-22 APG. By the mid-2010s, the trend has reversed and has continually increased to this current 2021 season.

Unsurprisingly, most of the winningest teams are located above the league average, while most of the losers are located below the line. For background information, "ball movement" is a common basketball term which relates to how often teammates pass to each other on offense before shooting the ball. This results in a more fluid offense which can create lapses in the opponent's defense more easily than an offense in which players pass less and attempt to score by themselves. Many of the top teams in history have had elite coaches (such as Gregg Popovich and Phil Jackson) who prioritize ball movement in their philosophy, and it is no wonder that these top teams display elite passing ability as reflected by their assist numbers. Many of the winners also happen to be the teams who achieved the maximum assists.

<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fe0465ea7f0>

The graph above depicts the average league-wide points per game in every season, from 1980 to the present. The league average starts out at around 110 PPG. Then it drops significantly throughout the 1990s to about 90 PPG before steadily rising for 2000 to 2020 and reaching 110 PPG again. The same trend can be seen across the winners and losers. This does not mean that teams in the middle years were worse at scoring. Instead it is largely due to how the pace of the game has changed. Teams in the 1980s such as the Showtime Lakers emphasized fast-paced offense while teams in the 90s and 00s emphasized slower pace and tough, hard-nosed defense, resulting in much lower PPG. From then on, the pace began to increase again, especially as the 3-Point revolution arrived. With the goal of basketball being to outscore the opponent to win the game, it is not surprising that those teams who put up greater than average PPG numbers were generally the winningest teams, while those who had less scoring ability were almost always the worst teams.

There are a few outliers however. For instance, the 2004/05 San Antonio Spurs (blue dot in the middle of the 2000s below the line) only scored 91.5 PPG (average was 97.2 PPG), yet they achieved the most wins that season and even won the NBA championship. On the other hand, the 2008/09 Sacramento Kings managed to score 100.6 PPG (above the league average of 100.0 PPG) but still won the fewest games. These outliers occur because the outcome of games do not depend only on offense and PPG, but defense as well. In the case of the Spurs, they had always been one of the best defensive teams which allowed them to hold their opponent to even lower PPG, while the Kings were on the opposite end of the defensive spectrum.

The graph above depicts the average league-wide steals per game in every season. The league average starts out at around 9.5 SPG and slowly but steadily decreases, with a few spikes in the 90s. It is also a reflection of how the general skill level of players has evolved and improved, as players today have much more impressive and sophisticated ball-handling and dribbling skills, allowing them to better control the ball and avoid it being stolen as easily as the less-skilled players of the 80s.

The two graphs above depict the average league-wide 3-pointers made and attempted per game in every season. The general shape and trend of both graphs are the same. 3-pointers made starts out at about 1 per game and 3-point attempts start out at around 3 per game. During the earlier decades, 3-pointers were not considered good shots as they were very difficult to hit and teams preferred layups and closer jumpshots instead, so practicing them was not a heavy point of emphasis for players. Winners and losers are located closely to each other and we do not see a general relationship between 3-pointers and the performance of the team.

Both graphs steadily rise and experience a great spike in the mid-90s before dropping back by 2000, but still more than the average before the spike. The rise continues and beginning in about 2013, we can see that the slope of the line begins to increase. In this era we see a sharp change because the winners and losers are clearly separated much further apart than earlier decades, with those who make and attempt more than league average very likely to be achieve the most wins, and those who make and attempt less very likely to achieve the fewest wins. This is largely due to the 3-point revolution as teams discovered that by taking and making more 3-pointers, it would open up their entire offense and make them more dynamic. Defenders would have to respect the improved shooting ability of players, so they would be dragged out to the 3-point line, resulting in less defense near the rim and making it easier for the offensive players to attack the rim. Many teams like the "Seven Seconds or Less" Phoenix Suns of the mid 2000s provided the blueprint of these fast-paced offensive schemes, and terrific shooters such as Stephen Curry of the Golden State Warriors took it a step further in the mid 2010s by attempting and hitting many more 3-pointers than anyone could previously imagine.

The data in these 2 graphs show how overall, 3-point ability is very closely tied to success in the league. The Assist and Points graph also support these graphs and they underline how teams with greater than average offensive firepower, ball movement, and 3-point shooting ability were very likely to achieve many wins, and how these 3 factors have become increasingly important in recent years compared to earlier decades like the 80s and 90s.

Conclusion¶

Our main goals for the project were to see the importance that 3 point shooting has on a team's performance in the leage. While analysing the data we can see thatt the winners for that year had higher 3 point shooting, attempt, percetange and goals than the average. While they may not have had the max, it's still very evident that while 3 point shooting is important to the success of a team, it's not the be all, end all form of scoring. This also stands for 2 point shooting. While the winners didn't have the max they were still above average. This leads us to believe that no form of scoring is the most important way to win. Even defensively the winners for that year arn't the highest in blocks or steals most of the time. The conclusion we reach is that no one stat is the most important in basketball. It is impossible to max out in an area in order to guarantee success. Success within the NBA comes from a well rounded team that is developed in all aspects of the game. Defense, 3P shooting, 2P shooting, assists, and steals all carry the same weight of importance to success.
